'''National Institute of Immunology''' ('''NII''') is an autonomous research institute located in [[New Delhi]],<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Gupta | first1 = KR | last2 = Gupta | first2 = Amit| date = 6 July 2006 | title = Concise Encyclopaedia of India, Volume 3 | url = https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=9dNOT9iYxcMC&pg=PA917&dq=national+institute+of+immunology+india&hl=en&sa=X&ei=wtIaVMTeDc2PuATLm4KoBA&ved=0CHQQ6AEwEA#v=onepage&q=national%20institute%20of%20immunology%20india&f=false | publisher = Atlantic Publishers & Distributors | page = 917 | isbn = 9788126906390}}</ref><ref name="GhoseGhosh2003">{{cite book|last1=Ghose|first1=T.K.|last2=Ghosh|first2=P.|title=Biotechnology in India I|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=77z8YXG4oLEC&pg=PA6|date=2003|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-3-540-00609-1|pages=6–}}</ref>  under the [[Department of Biotechnology]] (DBT) for research in [[immunology]].<ref>{{cite web | title = National Institute of Immunology | work = Department of Biotechnology, Government of India | url = http://dbtindia.nic.in/uniquepage.asp?id_pk=127 | accessdate = 2014-09-20 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140730220300/http://dbtindia.nic.in/uniquepage.asp?id_pk=127 | archivedate = 2014-07-30 | df =  }}</ref>

NII was established on 24 June 1981, with Prof. [[M. G. K. Menon]] as Chairman of its governing body. It has its origins in the [[ICMR]]–WHO Research & Training Centre in Immunology at the [[AIIMS, New Delhi|All India Institute of Medical Sciences]] (AIIMS), Delhi, which was  merged with NII  in 1982.However, NII continued to function from AIIMS laboratory of its honorary Director Prof G.P. Talwar, till its new building was constructed in 1983, carved out of the [[Jawaharlal Nehru University, Delhi|Jawaharlal Nehru University]] (JNU) campus.<ref name=History>[http://www1.nii.res.in/aboutus/history History] National Institute of Immunology</ref> G.P. Talwar is the founder director of this institute.<ref>[http://www.ilbs.in/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=332&Itemid=112 Prof. G. P. Talwar] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121093803/http://www.ilbs.in/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=332&Itemid=112 |date=2015-01-21 }} [[Institute of Liver and Biliary Sciences]] (ILBS)</ref> A first of its kind vaccine for leprosyin India have been developed by NII and it was named as mycobacterium indicus prani.{{fact|date=October 2018}}

